<html><head></head><body dir=3D"auto" style=3D"overflow-wrap: =
break-word; -webkit-nbsp-mode: space; line-break: after-white-space;">Hi =
Chris,<div><br></div><div><div><div>,</div><div><br></div><div>Thank you =
again for sending through the scope of works from Asset Restore and for =
helping move things forward. I=E2=80=99ve had a chance to review the =
document and I really appreciate the effort to progress the =
reinstatement.</div><div><br></div><div>Before we proceed, I wanted to =
raise a few questions that I hope you won=E2=80=99t mind me asking. My =
intention is to make sure that everything is being addressed safely and =
in the right order, and I=E2=80=99m asking these not to delay anything =
but because I want to feel confident that all risks have been properly =
considered.</div><div><br></div><div>A qualified master electrician has =
already assessed the house and advised that it is not electrically safe, =
particularly in relation to the new switchboard and wiring. Has a formal =
licensed electrical inspection been =
scheduled?</div><div><br></div><div>In terms of the structure, I=E2=80=99m=
 concerned about the extent of the smoke and heat. As you know, a large =
amount of smoke travelled up and out of the roof, which suggests that =
heat may have passed through structural elements like beams, ceilings, =
walls and floors. Would it be safer to have a structural engineer assess =
the property before further demolition or =
cleaning?</div><div><br></div><div>With respect to asbestos, the quote =
notes less than 10m=C2=B2 of ACM material to be removed, but from what I =
can see (and from the photos), the damaged section of the lower deck =
appears closely connected to the main deck above and may be more =
extensive than estimated. Would a full asbestos inspection be advisable =
just to rule out any broader risk?</div><div><br></div><div>There=E2=80=99=
s also the gas unit to consider. Given the heat and smoke in that area, =
has a technician been organised to check the system and =
fittings?</div><div><br></div><div>And lastly, I wanted to ask about =
moisture damage. A significant amount of water was used in firefighting, =
and the fire brigade shut off the water to the house due to leaking. =
Should we assess for possible water or mould damage in areas that may =
have been affected but aren=E2=80=99t immediately =
visible?</div><div><br></div><div>On a related note, I was wondering =
about the sequence of work. The quote appears to focus on cleaning for =
reinstatement, but would it perhaps make more sense to begin with =
removal and cleaning purely for the purpose of assessment? That way, =
once linings and affected areas are opened up, engineers and other =
specialists could properly evaluate the condition before decisions are =
made about reinstatement.</div><div><br></div><div>I also wanted to =
kindly ask if it=E2=80=99s possible to receive any plans, quotes, and =
key information a bit earlier. I understand that this quote had been =
available for about a week before I received it, and I only found out by =
calling today. I know everyone is busy and doing their best, but having =
earlier visibility would really help me feel informed and involved in =
the process.</div><div><br></div><div>Lastly, I want to say again that =
I=E2=80=99m very keen to move forward. The accommodation allowance is =
limited, and I truly want to return home and get life back to normal as =
soon as possible. These questions come from a place of care and =
cooperation, not delay.</div><div><br></div><div>Thanks again for your =
help, and I look forward to your reply.</div><div><br></div><div>Kind =
regards,</div><div>Raffaella del Prete</div></div><div><p dir=3D"auto" =
style=3D"white-space: pre-wrap;">Thank you so much for sending the Asset =
Restore scope of works and for all the work you=E2=80=99re putting into =
moving my claim forward. I really appreciate your support and the effort =
to get things rolling.</p><p dir=3D"auto" style=3D"white-space: =
pre-wrap;">As just discussed over the phone, I=E2=80=99d love to chat =
about a few things to ensure we=E2=80=99re covering all safety bases and =
tackling this in the best order. While I=E2=80=99m excited to move =
ahead, I would  feel more at ease knowing everything=E2=80=99s been =
thoroughly checked. I hope you don=E2=80=99t mind me asking=E2=80=94your =
guidance would be a huge help!</p><ul dir=3D"auto"><li>Could we =
prioritize these assessments first?<ul dir=3D"auto"><li>A master =
electrician has flagged the property as unsafe, particularly with the =
switchboard and cabling. Would it be possible to arrange a licensed =
electrical inspection to confirm safety before anyone =
re-enters?</li><li>As we spoke, there are structural beam damages, and =
the significant smoke traveling through floors, walls, and out all sides =
of the roof suggests extensive heat stress. The wetness and dampness =
created by firefighters might have added to the structural issues too. =
Might it be safer to have a structural engineer assess the building =
before any removal or cleaning starts?</li><li>The quote covers =
&lt;10m=C2=B2 ACM removal, but the attached photo shows the fire-damaged =
deck section connects to the larger area, hinting at more involvement. =
Could we schedule a full asbestos inspection to be certain?</li><li>The =
gas unit, located where heat and smoke hit hardest, is a concern. Would =
it be okay to have a gas technician check the fittings for =
safety?</li><li>The fire brigade=E2=80=99s water use and a subsequent =
leak shutdown suggest potential water damage or mould behind walls. =
Could we arrange a moisture/mould inspection before =
reinstatement?</li></ul></li><li>For safety and planning, would it make =
sense to start with cleaning and removal just for assessment purposes? =
This way, we can uncover any hidden damage (e.g., behind linings) and =
plan the full restoration with confidence. What do you =
think?</li></ul><p dir=3D"auto" style=3D"white-space: =
pre-wrap;"><br></p><p dir=3D"auto"><span style=3D"white-space-collapse: =
preserve;">I=E2=80=99d also love to receive plans, reports, and quotes =
ahead of time if possible so that Ican provide feedback would that work?
Please know I=E2=80=99m not trying to slow things down! I=E2=80=99m keen =
to get back home soon=E2=80=94the accommodation allowance is tight, and =
I miss my normal life. I just want to ensure we=E2=80=99re doing this =
safely and thoroughly. I=E2=80=99d be happy to discuss any of this =
whenever suits you.</span></p><p dir=3D"auto"><span style=3D"white-space: =
pre-wrap;">Thanks again for your support. Looking forward to your =
thoughts!</span></p><p dir=3D"auto" style=3D"white-space: =
pre-wrap;">Kind regards,<br>
Raffaella del =
Prete</p><div><br></div><div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div =
class=3D"AppleOriginalContents" style=3D"direction: ltr;"><blockquote =
